===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|walken||to move, roll, turn, revolve, toss|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|wealcan||to move round, revolve, roll, turn, toss|lang=ang}}, {{m|ang|ġewealcan||to go, traverse}}; and {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|walkien||to roll, stamp, walk, wallow|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|wealcian||to curl, roll up|lang=ang}}; both from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*walkaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*walkōną||to twist, turn, roll about, full}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*walg-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*walk-||to twist, turn, move}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|walk||to walk|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|swalkje||to wander, roam|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|walken||to full, work hair or felt|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|zwalken||to wander about|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|walken||to flex, full, mill, drum|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|valke||to waulk, full|lang=da}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|valgus||bandy-legged, bow-legged|lang=la}}. More at {{l|en|vagrant}}.

