===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[move]] on the [[feet]] by [[alternately]] [[setting]] each [[foot]] (or pair or group of feet, in the case of animals with four or more feet) [[forward]], with at least one foot on the [[ground]] at all times. Compare '''[[#Verb|run]]'''.
#: {{ux|en|To '''walk''' briskly for an hour every day is to keep fit.}}
#* {{RQ:WBsnt IvryGtP}}
#*: Athelstan Arundel walked home all the way, foaming and raging.{{...}}His mother lived at Pembridge Square, which is four good measured miles from Lincoln's Inn. He walked the whole way, '''walking''' through crowds, and under the noses of dray-horses, carriage-horses, and cart-horses, without taking the least notice of them.
#* {{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=15
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=Edward Churchill still attended to his work in a hopeless mechanical manner like a sleep-walker who '''walks''' safely on a well-known round. But his Roman collar galled him, his cossack stifled him, his biretta was as uncomfortable as a merry-andrew's cap and bells.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial|legal}} To "walk [[free]]", i.e. to win, or avoid, a criminal court case, particularly when [[actually]] [[guilty]].
#: {{ux|en|If you can’t present a better case, that robber is going to '''walk'''.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial|euphemistic}} Of an object, to be [[stolen]].
#: {{ux|en|If you leave your wallet lying around, it’s going to '''walk'''.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|cricket|of a batsman}} To walk off the field, as if [[given]] [[out]], after the [[fielding]] [[side]] [[appeal]]s and before the [[umpire]] has [[ruled]]; done as a matter of [[sportsmanship]] when the batsman believes he is out.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To travel (a distance) by walking.
#: {{ux|en|I '''walk''' two miles to school every day.&emsp; The museum’s not far from here &ndash; you can '''walk''' it.}}
#* {{RQ:WBsnt IvryGtP}}
#*: Athelstan Arundel '''walked''' home all the way, foaming and raging.{{...}}His mother lived at Pembridge Square, which is four good measured miles from Lincoln's Inn. He '''walked''' the whole way, walking through crowds, and under the noses of dray-horses, carriage-horses, and cart-horses, without taking the least notice of them.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To take for a walk or accompany on a walk.
#: {{ux|en|I '''walk''' the dog every morning.&emsp; Will you '''walk''' me home?}}
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}} (1564-1616)
#*: I will rather trust{{...}}a thief to '''walk''' my ambling gelding.
# {{lb|en|transitive|baseball}} To allow a batter to reach base by pitching four [[ball|balls]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To move something by [[shifting]] between two positions, as if it were walking.
#: {{ux|en|I carefully '''walked''' the ladder along the wall.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[full]]; to [[beat]] cloth to give it the consistency of [[felt]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[traverse]] by walking (or analogous gradual movement).
#: {{ux|en|I '''walked''' the streets aimlessly.&nbsp;&nbsp; Debugging this computer program involved '''walking''' the heap.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial}} To leave, resign.
#: {{ux|en|If we don't offer him more money he'll '''walk'''.}}
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: He will make their cows and garrans to '''walk'''.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To push (a vehicle) alongside oneself as one walks.
#* '''1994''', John Forester, ''Bicycle Transportation: A Handbook for Cycling Transportation Engineers'', MIT Press, [http://books.google.com/books?id=Qz4kAulpimgC&pg=PA245&dq=%22walked+his+bicycle%22 p.245]:
#*: The county had a successful defense only because the judge kept telling the jury at every chance that the cyclist should have '''walked''' his bicycle like a pedestrian.
# To behave; to pursue a course of life; to conduct oneself.
#* {{w|Jeremy Taylor}} (1613–1677)
#*: We '''walk''' perversely with God, and he will '''walk''' crookedly toward us.
# To be stirring; to be abroad; to go restlessly about; said of things or persons expected to remain quiet, such as a sleeping person, or the spirit of a dead person.
#* {{w|Hugh Latimer}} (c.1485-1555)
#*: I heard a pen '''walking''' in the chimney behind the cloth.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To be in motion; to act; to move.
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: Her tongue did '''walk''' in foul reproach.
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}} (1564-1616)
#*: I have heard, but not believed, the spirits of the dead / May '''walk''' again.
#* {{w|Ben Jonson}} (1572-1637)
#*: Do you think I'd '''walk''' in any plot?
# {{cx|transitive|historical|lang=en}} To put, keep, or train (a [[puppy]]) in a walk, or training area for [[dogfighting]].

